{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18050"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.04,0.11,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10764"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man trips and falls, hurting his right elbow. An X-ray reveals a fracture of the medial epicondyle of the humerus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most at risk of injury with this type of fracture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachial artery","Median nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is most at risk of injury in a fracture of the medial epicondyle of the humerus. The ulnar nerve runs in a groove behind the medial epicondyle, making it susceptible to trauma in this area. Injury to the ulnar nerve can result in sensory loss in the little finger and half of the ring finger, as well as weakness in the intrinsic muscles of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with fractures of the humeral shaft, particularly the midshaft, where it runs in the radial groove.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is typically at risk in supracondylar fractures of the humerus, especially in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial artery\u003C/strong\u003E is also at risk in supracondylar fractures, but not typically in fractures of the medial epicondyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely injured in elbow fractures, as it is located more proximally in the arm and is protected by the biceps muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ulnar nerve is at risk of injury in fractures of the medial epicondyle of the humerus.","The ulnar nerve runs in a groove behind the medial epicondyle, making it susceptible to trauma in this area."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18050"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T19:47:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T19:48:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"